-- U.K. Stocks Decline; Barclays, African Barrick Shares Lead FTSE 100 Lower
-- B y   A d a m   H a i g h
-- 2010-10-14T15:50:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-13/booker-clinton-cards-wh-smith-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks  declined amid
speculation that banks may need to raise more capital and as
 African Barrick Gold Plc  slumped after suspending staff in
Tanzania as gangs had infiltrated its operation to steal fuel.  Barclays Plc led bank shares lower, dropping 4.1 percent.
 African Barrick  posted its largest-ever plunge after saying it
suspended staff at its Buzwagi mine in the east African country
after discovering operations were “widely infiltrated” by
criminal gangs that were stealing its fuel.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  dropped 20.14, or 0.4 percent,
to 5,727.21 at the 4:30 p.m. close in London. The gauge has
rallied 19 percent since July 1 as investors speculated that the
Federal Reserve will announce plans to stimulate economic growth
in November as the recovery wanes. The  FTSE All-Share Index 
retreated 0.3 percent and Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  lost 1.2 percent
today.  The FTSE 350 Banks Index has lost 5.2 percent since the
beginning of August amid concern that new requirements under the
Basel III accord will require banks to raise more capital,
diluting shareholder value.  “Bank have actually weighed on the FTSE 100 Index for much
of the last four weeks on continued uncertainty over stricter
regulations,” said  Joshua Raymond , a markets strategists at
City Index Ltd. in London.  Barclays Declines  Barclays  lost 4.1 percent to 280 pence. Execution Noble
Ltd. downgraded the shares to “neutral” from “buy.”  “While a capital discount is in the price to some extent,
this is unlikely to be lifted until there is more clarity on any
‘U.K. finish’ and the bank addresses its capital structure post
Basel III,” London-based Execution Noble analyst  Fiona Swaffield  wrote in a report to clients today about Barclays.  Barclays President  Bob Diamond  said that the bank won’t
need additional funding from shareholders, even though Basel III
rules will affect its ability to generate earnings.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc retreated 4.7 percent to
45.3 pence and Lloyds Banking Group Plc sank 2.9 percent to 70.5
pence.  African Barrick tumbled 9.5 percent to 564 pence, its
biggest one day slide since its initial public offering in
March. The company suspended about 40 percent of employees at
the site’s mining department. The miner will produce about
30,000 ounces less this year as a result of the theft. The
company had already cut production by 10,000 ounces in the third
quarter.  WH Smith Plc  advanced 5.5 percent to 480 pence. The U.K.’s
biggest seller of magazines said it will return as much as 50
million pounds ($79.9 million) of cash to investors through a
“rolling share buyback.” WH Smith said full-year profit before
tax and exceptional items rose 9 percent to 89 million pounds in
the 12 months through August.  To contact the reporter on this story:
